@caveatlector2671 Actually, ESG bucks are the best deal in town, so of course the people raising the money for the production are going to check all the ESG boxes.  They basically get paid, no matter what, as soon as the financing is secured.  It's basically the plot of The Producers, running over and over again.  As long as those ESG bucks are there, Hollywood will keep making ESG movies.  It's as simple as that.

The only brake on that is the investors pulling back.  If the investors make enough money, elsewhere, by winning the culture wars, they can lose money on Hollywood, indefinitely.  This is why legacy media has a lot more momentum than the straight-up financial statements would indicate.  They can lose money forever, as long as there's a rich man who thinks he can benefit by controlling the narrative on those outlets.

Eventually, people just lose faith and interest.  Then those outlets will die back, and some other approach to dominating the public square will be taken.

